			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">When you get into the "gotta level gotta level gotta level gotta level gotta level gotta level gotta level" mindset, you open yourself up to a HUGE disappointment. I would think that people who have played EQ for so many years would have learned this by now. 
<br />

<br />
So you level and level and level and level and level. One day, you reach the top. What then? One of 3 options: 
<br />
1. Declare "victory" and walk away, as many in EQ did, only to be seriously disappointed by SOE raising the level cap umpteen times. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
To each his own. I remember a time when being on the cutting edge was very important to me and I had a blast playing that way. Now I'm quite the opposite, but it really doesn't matter, regardless.
<br />

<br />
When I began mmogs I was younger, single, and lived with friends who all gamed. My lifestyle was geared to game and it was awesome. MMOG's were new and fresh and immersion was intense, the sky was the limit. The "upper levels" were undiscovered and seemed godly. 
<br />

<br />
Years later everything that can happen in any game has been done or at least I have some expectation or predetermined idea.. there is no mystical magical "unknown." I play when I can and enjoy it at whatever level. I actually prefer not being pressured by others and therefore solo quite a bit. There's a lot to be said for the immersive solitude of wandering around in an mmog, progressing and discovering at one's own pace.<br />_________________<br /><img src="http://home.comcast.net/~drdeathbane/images/scarecroweIV.gif" border="0" />
<br />
<a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=917876" target="_blank" class="postlink">magelo</a>
